# ESLint Editor Discipline (`source.fixAll.eslint` + editor-config split)

Type-aware ESLint rules (`@typescript-eslint/no-floating-promises`,
`no-misused-promises`, `no-unsafe-*`, `await-thenable`, etc.) are CI-safe
but editor-hostile: they force the parser to load the full TypeScript
program for each lint pass, costing ~3-5x inline-feedback latency and
several hundred MB extra ESLint-server RAM. Worse, when a project also
has `source.fixAll.eslint: true` in `.vscode/settings.json` or its
Cursor equivalent, the typescript-eslint auto-fixer is allowed to:

- silently strip `eslint-disable` directives that look "unused" against
  a transient rule state,
- rewrite type assertions in ways that break `tsc --noEmit`.

This rule fires when the AI is configuring editor settings or editing
ESLint config. It does **not** apply to source files.

## Rules

- When configuring or modifying any editor-settings file (`.vscode/settings.json`, `.cursor/settings.json`, equivalent host configs), `source.fixAll.eslint` MUST be `"explicit"`. Never `true`. Never `"always"`. Any change that introduces `true` is a bug.
- When a project ships an `eslint.config.editor.{js,mjs,cjs}` (a thinner editor-only config that strips type-aware rules), the editor's ESLint extension MUST point at that file via `eslint.options.overrideConfigFile`. CI keeps using the production `eslint.config.{js,mjs,cjs}`. Do not silently flip the override back to the production config "to see all warnings" in the editor.
- Do NOT add type-aware rules to `eslint.config.editor.*`. The whole point of an editor-only config is to skip them. If a future Phase adds a new type-aware rule to production, append the rule name to the editor config's filter list (e.g. `TYPE_AWARE_RULES`), do not duplicate the rule into the editor config.
- Do NOT recommend `eslint --fix` as a routine workflow. Use focused fixes. For bulk auto-fix passes, gate behind explicit user confirmation per `23-eslint-flat-config-hygiene.mdc`.
- When a contributor reports IDE lag / high RAM / "ESLint server unresponsive" in a project that has type-aware rules, first check whether the project ships a `.vscode/settings.json.example` (or equivalent) the contributor needs to copy. The default extension behavior (no override) loads the production config and triggers the cost.

## Anti-patterns (do not ship)

- `"source.fixAll.eslint": true` in any committed settings file.
- `"source.fixAll.eslint": "always"` (same effect as `true`).
- Adding type-aware rules directly to `eslint.config.editor.*`.
- Removing a `linterOptions.reportUnusedDisableDirectives: "off"` block from `eslint.config.editor.*` — that block typically exists precisely so editors don't flag (and `source.fixAll` doesn't auto-strip) `eslint-disable` directives that target rules the editor config has stripped.
- Suggesting contributors run `eslint --fix` to "clean up the warnings the editor shows" without first checking whether those warnings come from the production config (legitimate) or the editor config (which intentionally hides them).

## See also

- `23-eslint-flat-config-hygiene.mdc` — production-config hygiene rules (rule promotion stages, flat-config block ordering, inline-disable reasons).
- The consuming project's `docs/LINTING.md` (or equivalent) — the project-specific story for rule rollout, editor config, and recommended settings.
